WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.780 --> 00:00:05.830
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: We're delighted to have
Dr. David Agus joining us today.

00:00:05.830 --> 00:00:11.230
He's a professor of medicine and engineering
at USC, and heads up the Westside Cancer Center

00:00:11.230 --> 00:00:15.960
and the Center for Applied Molecular Medicine
there at USC.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:20.670
He clearly excels in business as much as he
does in academics.

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:23.590
He's the cofounder of two personalized medicine
companies.

00:00:23.590 --> 00:00:27.160
One is Navigenics and the other is Applied
Proteomics.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:33.390
His recently published book, The End of Illness,
calls for a shift in the fundamental ways

00:00:33.390 --> 00:00:37.161
in which we think about the actions of health
and illness, including a view of the body

00:00:37.161 --> 00:00:42.230
as a complex system rather than a series of
simple causal chains.

00:00:42.230 --> 00:00:47.159
He balances this philosophical approach with
a very practical one, laying out recommended

00:00:47.159 --> 00:00:52.390
annual health checkpoints, lab results that
you should have done regularly, and why you

00:00:52.390 --> 00:00:56.820
should not sit down all day at your job.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:01:02.829
His book is really, for me, was all about
prevention and how to keep yourself healthy,

00:01:02.829 --> 00:01:09.080
which is an area that both Google and Googlers
need to own as we grow older.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:15.460
If all of that somehow left you in doubt about
his brilliance, Dr. Agus also has achieved

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:17.119
a degree of celebrity stardom.

00:01:17.119 --> 00:01:22.930
He was on the Daily Show a few weeks ago with
Jon Stewart.

00:01:22.930 --> 00:01:28.909
I guess what we're really all wondering is
what Jon Stewart says to his guests as he

00:01:28.909 --> 00:01:32.149
leans over the desk as the camera pans out.

00:01:32.149 --> 00:01:34.430
With that, I welcome Dr. David Agus.

00:01:34.430 --> 00:01:35.430
[applause]

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:38.030
&gt;&gt;David Agus: Thank you.

00:01:38.030 --> 00:01:43.000
It's funny, Jon Stewart-- Before the show,
I went up to him and I said, "I'm scared to

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:44.000
death.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:45.000
I'm a cancer doc.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:47.799
I do all this media, but being live with a
comic scares me a little."

00:01:47.799 --> 00:01:50.030
And he said, "Listen, I'll give you a hint.

00:01:50.030 --> 00:01:53.460
Most people at the end of the show stand up
and leave, but there's 30 seconds when the

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:54.750
credits roll.

00:01:54.750 --> 00:01:56.110
You lean forward and talk to me.

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:57.539
People will think we're friends, and it will
work."

00:01:57.539 --> 00:02:02.210
[laughter] Then I lean forward at the end
and he goes, "The deal was for me to have

00:02:02.210 --> 00:02:03.929
told you this, is now you have to be my doctor."

00:02:03.929 --> 00:02:08.490
[laughter]
It's a pleasure to be here.

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:09.630
Thank you.

00:02:09.630 --> 00:02:13.170
The End of Illness is a declaratory, aggressive
title.

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:15.830
I submitted it to the publisher about 8, 9
months ago.

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:19.910
It was called, at the time, What Is Health?,
as an homage to Schrödinger's What Is Life?

00:02:19.910 --> 00:02:20.910
book from the 1940s.

00:02:20.910 --> 00:02:25.260
I had a call from the publisher saying, "Agus,
Steve Jobs just called and changed the title

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:26.260
of your book."

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:27.710
I'm like, "He did?"

00:02:27.710 --> 00:02:29.560
And they're like, "He changed it to The End
of Illness."

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:34.269
I called Steve, and I said, "Steve, I love
the title, but why didn't you tell me or discuss

00:02:34.269 --> 00:02:35.269
it with me?"

00:02:35.269 --> 00:02:36.670
He goes, "Agus, it's not your job.

00:02:36.670 --> 00:02:37.670
It's theirs."

00:02:37.670 --> 00:02:38.790
I was like, "Okay."

00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:41.550
I thought about it, and it is obviously and
aggressive title.

00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:43.150
But it's something I believe in.

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:47.220
I truly believe we can delay illness to the
ninth or tenth decade.

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:52.549
If you look in the United States, 1956 was
the last year you can die of old age on a

00:02:52.549 --> 00:02:53.970
death certificate.

00:02:53.970 --> 00:02:59.400
Since then, we've had to have a cause, whether
it be diabetes or lung cancer or prostate

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:00.400
cancer.

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:01.400
You name it, there had to be a cause.

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:04.860
But I want to go back to the era of dying
of old age.

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:10.470
The paradox is in that if we delay illness
to the ninth or tenth decade, healthcare costs

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:13.319
will come down dramatically.

00:03:13.319 --> 00:03:19.239
If you get ill in your 80s and 90s or 100s,
actually, you don't go to an intensive care

00:03:19.239 --> 00:03:20.239
unit.

00:03:20.239 --> 00:03:21.239
You don't go on a ventilator.

00:03:21.239 --> 00:03:24.269
We treat you with dignity instead of trying
to prolong things.

00:03:24.269 --> 00:03:28.720
Remember, over 60% of healthcare costs in
the United States right now are the last two

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:30.280
years of life.

00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:34.240
We spend almost nothing from age 15 to age
55.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:37.900
Obviously, part of the premise that I want
to push to you is we've got to shift that

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:39.700
because we have to prevent illness.

00:03:39.700 --> 00:03:45.890
We are the number 1 spender in the world on
healthcare, and we're ranked 32nd.

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:50.610
Washington has ex bandwidth for health, and
most of it, if not all of it, is spent on

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:51.650
healthcare finance.

00:03:51.650 --> 00:03:53.140
None of it's spent on health.

00:03:53.140 --> 00:03:57.849
What I'm going to present you today is a new
way of looking at health and really focusing

00:03:57.849 --> 00:04:00.159
on what I think we need to do as changes.

00:04:00.159 --> 00:04:02.969
The book came out 3, 4 weeks ago.

00:04:02.969 --> 00:04:07.730
What's amazing is I've already had about 6,
now, video conferences with member of the

00:04:07.730 --> 00:04:08.730
Chinese government.

00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:11.560
They're going to enact parts of the book as
law this summer.

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:15.490
Whereas the US government, it will take a
decade of debate before they even bring it

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:18.209
up to talk about it publicly.

00:04:18.209 --> 00:04:22.660
The first question when I talk about this
book is everyone says, "You're a cancer doctor.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:26.830
Why do you have the right to publish this
book and talk about it?"

00:04:26.830 --> 00:04:30.889
To me, it comes from the old adage that in
order to understand peace, you have to go

00:04:30.889 --> 00:04:32.320
to war.

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:36.860
Fighting cancer for the last 25 years has
brought, in my mind, a whole new way of approaching

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:37.860
health.

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:43.760
The team that I work with are two other individuals
who bring very unique ways of looking at health.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:45.419
I've got Murray Gell-Mann.

00:04:45.419 --> 00:04:47.680
Murray is probably the greatest living physicist.

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:50.030
Discovered the quark, string theory.

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:51.620
He won the Nobel Prize in 1969.

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:55.820
Now, he's working on modeling health with
our team.

00:04:55.820 --> 00:05:00.040
And a guy named Danny Hillis, who built the
first supercomputer and discovered RAID storage

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:04.590
in the old days, and is again one of the great
engineers who is now working on modeling health

00:05:04.590 --> 00:05:05.590
now.

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:10.810
What you'll see is the result of us thinking
about health or approaching it as a biologist,

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:12.389
a physicist, and an engineer.

00:05:12.389 --> 00:05:16.610
I'll show you a new model, looking at health
as a complex emergent system as disease in

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:21.470
the body, how one can apply it, so it will
be prescriptive, and then how technology is

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:26.860
going to be, in my mind, what allows us and
brings us the hope to actually bring us change.

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:28.949
The first question is: what is health?

00:05:28.949 --> 00:05:29.949
Is it your cholesterol?

00:05:29.949 --> 00:05:30.949
Is it your weight?

00:05:30.949 --> 00:05:31.949
Is it how you feel?

00:05:31.949 --> 00:05:32.949
Is it how you sleep?

00:05:32.949 --> 00:05:33.949
Is it how you look?

00:05:33.949 --> 00:05:35.440
How do you define health?

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:39.699
Any engineer will tell you it's impossible
to optimize a system unless you develop parameters

00:05:39.699 --> 00:05:41.270
on which to optimize.

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:42.270
So what is it?

00:05:42.270 --> 00:05:43.509
Is it how long you live?

00:05:43.509 --> 00:05:45.289
Is it what you look like?

00:05:45.289 --> 00:05:48.009
On what parameter are we going to optimize
health?

00:05:48.009 --> 00:05:49.870
We don't have a blood test for health.

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:54.420
If I asked you today, "Are you healthy?",
how do you respond?

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:58.729
That's one of the fundamental problems is
I don't know how to define health when I look

00:05:58.729 --> 00:06:00.270
at it.

00:06:00.270 --> 00:06:04.550
We can talk about all the corporate wellness
programs in the world, but corporate wellness

00:06:04.550 --> 00:06:09.199
programs will optimize on lowering health
insurance costs.

00:06:09.199 --> 00:06:12.490
Corporate illness programs are about delaying
illness till retirement.

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:15.479
But I want to figure out a way to optimize
health.

00:06:15.479 --> 00:06:19.139
We'll talk about ways I think we could start
to do that, going forward.

00:06:19.139 --> 00:06:23.479
Mark Twain, in his imminent wisdom, said,
"The only way to keep your health is to eat

00:06:23.479 --> 00:06:26.610
what you don't want, drink what you don't
like, and do what you'd rather not."

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:30.819
[laughter] When I asked Steve, "Why didn't
you like the title What Is Health?"

00:06:30.819 --> 00:06:35.240
He said, "If you put the word health in the
title, people think of chewing cardboard."

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:40.400
That's part of the problem, is that health
is something that we know we're not going

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:43.639
to like if you say what you have to do.

00:06:43.639 --> 00:06:46.600
Things that are unhealthy are more appealing.

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:50.490
What I'll try to show you today is that that's
not really the case.

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:54.370
By definition, things in health don't have
to be unappealing.

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:57.169
Again, we go to what is that metric for health.

00:06:57.169 --> 00:07:01.470
Well, in the United States, we spent over
a billion dollars last year in people over

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:03.129
the age of 50 getting growth hormone.

00:07:03.129 --> 00:07:04.129
Why?

00:07:04.129 --> 00:07:08.199
If I give you growth hormone at age 50, 60,
or 70, you're going to look better in a couple

00:07:08.199 --> 00:07:09.199
of months.

00:07:09.199 --> 00:07:10.289
You're going to be all buff.

00:07:10.289 --> 00:07:12.150
Your friends are going to come and be all,
"Hey, what happened to you?

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:13.150
Did you get a haircut?

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:14.150
You look great."

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:15.310
You're going to feel better.

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:19.360
You're going to live, on average, 12 or 13
years less.

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:20.360
But you're going to look better.

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:23.200
And yet, our country, we do this all the time.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:27.479
People go in, especially in my city, Los Angeles,
and they get shots of growth hormone to look

00:07:27.479 --> 00:07:28.479
better.

00:07:28.479 --> 00:07:32.730
They take, whether it be steroids, they get
Botox, they get all kinds of things to look

00:07:32.730 --> 00:07:33.730
better.

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:37.169
But again, I want people to think about tomorrow
as well as today.

00:07:37.169 --> 00:07:41.450
There's an amazing group of people in Ecuador
that was identified in a paper in Science

00:07:41.450 --> 00:07:43.259
this last year, where they actually looked.

00:07:43.259 --> 00:07:46.440
They have a mutation of the growth hormone
receptor.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:51.330
These people don't get cancer and don't get
diabetes at all in their populations.

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:57.659
They have other problems, but what we also
know is that species that grow larger or members

00:07:57.659 --> 00:08:00.550
of a species that grow larger have more health
problems.

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:04.300
And yet, we as a society push to making people
larger.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:05.890
One of the chapters of the book is about football
players.

00:08:05.890 --> 00:08:11.409
Football players are, in general, very large,
have a lot of inflammation, as we'll talk

00:08:11.409 --> 00:08:12.409
about.

00:08:12.409 --> 00:08:15.160
CNN did a story on this for the Super Bowl.

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:18.240
I can't tell you how many hate emails I got,
and letters.

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:20.139
"You're taking away American culture."

00:08:20.139 --> 00:08:21.360
"You're screwing us."

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:24.210
I'm not against football, but I'm against
the concept of inflammation.

00:08:24.210 --> 00:08:28.880
I'm against the concept of the bigger, the
better, as we'll talk about.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:31.860
We need to start to identify what are the
metrics each of us individually are going

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:35.840
to look at, because obviously, we want to
live until our 90s.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.130
The key is avoid disease.

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:40.710
I look at 2 to 3 people a week, and I say,
"I've got no more drugs to treat your cancer.

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:41.710
I've run out.

00:08:41.710 --> 00:08:43.500
And unfortunately, the cancer's going to win."

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:45.320
I don't want to do that anymore.

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:47.940
The way to stop that is to avoid disease.

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:49.790
Most diseases can be delayed or avoided.

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:56.420
I don't know if you guys saw the paper last
week, but now we'll make Alzheimer's a disease

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:59.130
of the past over the next 5 to 7 years.

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:03.350
It's astonishing, but Alzheimer's will go
away.

00:09:03.350 --> 00:09:08.210
If you look at it, a month ago, 15% of us
in the room will be affected by Alzheimer's.

00:09:08.210 --> 00:09:10.090
As of the data last week, it's staggering.

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:11.260
There are two big advances.

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:15.751
The first is they took a couple of cells that
made this abnormal protein called tau, which

00:09:15.751 --> 00:09:18.760
is what messes up the brain in Alzheimer's.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:20.700
They put them in the brain of a mouse.

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:23.190
Then they sacrificed the mouse a couple weeks
later.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:26.010
And what do you know: those tangles are all
over the brain.

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:30.350
So Alzheimer's isn't a disease of the brain,
it's a disease of a couple cells that then

00:09:30.350 --> 00:09:33.020
spreads its proteins throughout the brain.

00:09:33.020 --> 00:09:37.360
If you block that, you no longer will have
Alzheimer's.

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:39.560
We have a mouse model now that's accurate.

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:40.591
We can develop it.

00:09:40.591 --> 00:09:43.660
Instead of testing in humans-- The problems
in testing in patients is you've got to do

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:44.660
it for ten years.

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:49.190
You're not going to know until-- ahh!-- ten
years later whether it worked or not.

00:09:49.190 --> 00:09:50.410
So now we've got a model.

00:09:50.410 --> 00:09:55.090
And then, get a load of this, they took a
drug for lymphoma that had been FDA approved

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:58.260
already, it's on the market, and they gave
it to these mice.

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:03.010
Well, if a mouse-- You drop a napkin in a
cage, they chew it up and make a little nest.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:04.410
It's called nesting.

00:10:04.410 --> 00:10:09.040
You give a mouse Alzheimer's, they just sit
in a corner and act like this and do nothing.

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:13.000
You give them this drug for lymphoma with
the Alzheimer's, two days later, they're making

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.470
a nest again.

00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:18.640
You look in the brain of the animal, 60% of
these tangles are gone.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:22.970
Again, this is a drug that's already FDA approved
and on the market.

00:10:22.970 --> 00:10:26.740
So we're going to have a marked impact on
Alzheimer's and every disease we'll talk about

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:27.740
today.

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:31.750
The key is delaying them or preventing them
so you, I, our loved ones, can benefit from

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:35.760
those advances.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.200
And again, we talked about that it's actually
going to lower costs if we do this right.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:41.320
In the 1930s, J.B.S.

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:45.960
Haldane, who was the great thinker of the
time, said this amazing quote, because it

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:47.080
really is true today.

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:48.080
He was right.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:49.890
He predicted it 90 years ago.

00:10:49.890 --> 00:10:54.860
He said, "Bacteria and this germ theory is
going to screw up everything because we're

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:56.740
going to forget about the system.”

00:10:56.740 --> 00:11:01.450
We're going to treat other diseases like cancer,
heart disease, and Alzheimer's like infectious

00:11:01.450 --> 00:11:03.440
disease, and we're going to be wrong.

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:04.620
He was right.

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:08.690
Remember, infectious disease, you make the
diagnosis, you know the treatment.

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:09.710
It's easy.

00:11:09.710 --> 00:11:12.770
That bacteria, that antibiotic, they work.

00:11:12.770 --> 00:11:16.610
It doesn't care if you're short, round, tall,
fat, green, yellow, blue.

00:11:16.610 --> 00:11:20.400
It will work because bacteria come from without.

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:23.450
The problem is, human disease comes from within.

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:27.500
Human disease, you make a diagnosis, most
of the time you don't know the treatment because

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:32.420
it's the interaction of that disease in your
body that's unique in each of us.

00:11:32.420 --> 00:11:34.230
Very different from infectious disease.

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:39.050
Yet, over the last 90 years, we've been treating
almost all disease like infectious disease.

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:41.140
You have X, let me give you Y.

00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:45.020
Most of the time, unfortunately, that doesn't
work.

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:49.701
This is one of the sad figures that's in the
book that I get a lot of comments about, which

00:11:49.701 --> 00:11:55.160
is heart disease, stroke, down dramatically
in death rate over the last 50 years.

00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:57.060
Cancer, not really a change.

00:11:57.060 --> 00:11:59.620
Well, what caused this major decline?

00:11:59.620 --> 00:12:00.980
Two things.

00:12:00.980 --> 00:12:03.270
Smoking: we're smoking less.

00:12:03.270 --> 00:12:09.390
And then statins: statins are class of drug
that were developed to lower LDL, the bad

00:12:09.390 --> 00:12:12.040
cholesterol, and then they were given to patients.

00:12:12.040 --> 00:12:14.210
They had a dramatic effect on heart disease
and stroke.

00:12:14.210 --> 00:12:18.680
Turns out that their mechanism, how they work,
was different than lowering cholesterol, as

00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:19.680
I will talk about.

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:23.760
It's because they're one of the great anti-inflammatory
drugs we have.

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:26.760
The root of diseases like heart disease and
cancer inflammation.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:32.500
In fact, statins will reduce the incidence
of cancer beautifully if one takes them for

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:33.890
several years.

00:12:33.890 --> 00:12:40.110
So, dramatic effect here, yet influenza, right:
we can give vaccines, we have antibiotics,

00:12:40.110 --> 00:12:41.110
fantastic.

00:12:41.110 --> 00:12:43.690
Cancer, not really a big impact.

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:47.290
So cancer, we've treated a reductionist way.

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:51.020
The amazing thing about cancer that people
don't get is-- Again, I was one of the heads

00:12:51.020 --> 00:12:54.190
of the Cancer Genome Project, so I'm as guilty
as anybody else.

00:12:54.190 --> 00:12:57.940
But if you look at breast cancer under a microscope,
a pathologist will look and say, "Hey, it's

00:12:57.940 --> 00:12:58.940
breast cancer."

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:00.430
They don't care what the genetics are.

00:13:00.430 --> 00:13:02.290
The body doesn't care what the genetics are.

00:13:02.290 --> 00:13:04.270
Breast cancer looks like breast cancer.

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:07.060
Colon cancer looks like colon cancer.

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:11.450
Evolution is selecting out for phenotype,
what it looks like, not the underlying genetics.

00:13:11.450 --> 00:13:15.810
There are 150 ways to get to be breast cancer,
yet they all look alike.

00:13:15.810 --> 00:13:19.000
Yet our treatments, we keep trying to hit
those molecular abnormalities.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.050
We forget the other part.

00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:25.990
A clinical trial was done about 10 years ago
that people thought was crazy, that now is

00:13:25.990 --> 00:13:29.670
the standard of care in the treatment of a
disease, breast cancer.

00:13:29.670 --> 00:13:32.130
What we did was it took women after optimal
treatment.

00:13:32.130 --> 00:13:37.770
Half got placebo, and half got a drug that
builds bone, a drug for osteoporosis.

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:41.990
Recurrence was reduced by 40% Why?

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:43.790
Breast cancer metastasizes to bone.

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:47.240
If you change the soil, the seed doesn't grow.

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:50.190
We just made the body inhospitable to breast
cancer.

00:13:50.190 --> 00:13:53.450
And what do you know, it didn't come back
in those women.

00:13:53.450 --> 00:13:56.650
A powerful statement, a powerful way to treat
disease.

00:13:56.650 --> 00:14:01.860
Because to me, diseases like cancer, Alzheimer's,
heart disease, they are verbs, not nouns.

00:14:01.860 --> 00:14:03.070
You're cancering.

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:05.260
You're heart diseasing.

00:14:05.260 --> 00:14:09.420
I want to change you from that disease state
to a health state.

00:14:09.420 --> 00:14:16.940
It's a different way of approaching disease
if you think about it.

00:14:16.940 --> 00:14:20.270
The way I look at it is at a complex emergent
system, where you've got inputs.

00:14:20.270 --> 00:14:21.450
Your input is your DNA.

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:23.190
Your input's what you eat.

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:24.190
It's your environment.

00:14:24.190 --> 00:14:25.290
It's your work environment.

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:26.540
It's your friends.

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:27.700
Those are all your inputs.

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:30.160
Your output is how you feel.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:34.140
That middle state function has been historically
hidden.

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:35.910
We haven't been able to look at it.

00:14:35.910 --> 00:14:39.500
Historically, we give change in input and
we see how it affects the output, with all

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:40.500
those inputs.

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:41.860
But we've never been able to look in the middle.

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:46.940
Well, on the cover of the book, let me just
borrow this for one sec, we can all of a sudden

00:14:46.940 --> 00:14:48.810
see the state function.

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:50.620
This is a picture of the human proteome.

00:14:50.620 --> 00:14:55.480
It's a drop of blood going through a supercomputer,
I mean a superconducting magnet, where we

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:59.760
get a 50 to 60 gigabyte image of all the proteins
in the blood.

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:00.840
That's that state function.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:02.810
For the first time, we can see.

00:15:02.810 --> 00:15:05.470
We'll talk about that a little more in a minute.

00:15:05.470 --> 00:15:09.690
But all of a sudden, you've got various state
functions that are equivalent classes of history.

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:12.570
They are patients with heart disease, patients
with cancer.

00:15:12.570 --> 00:15:13.920
We can start to modulate them.

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:17.490
For the first time now with technology, we
can actually see them.

00:15:17.490 --> 00:15:24.420
Well, the bad news is it is almost impossible
to understand complex emergent systems.

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:28.330
The good news is, you can control the systems
you can't understand.

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:32.760
If I asked my 11 year old boy, "How do you
stop a train?", he just says, "You pull the

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:33.760
brake."

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:35.520
He doesn't first say, "What's the weight of
the train?

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:36.520
What's the track made of?

00:15:36.520 --> 00:15:37.520
What's the temperature?

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:38.680
What's the air speed?"

00:15:38.680 --> 00:15:39.680
He just says, "Listen.

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:41.770
I've got to figure out a way to control it."

00:15:41.770 --> 00:15:46.560
My field has spent the last 50 years trying
to understand diseases like cancer rather

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:49.690
than just working on ways to optimize and
control them.

00:15:49.690 --> 00:15:53.730
The average cancer on diagnosis has how many
mutations?

00:15:53.730 --> 00:15:55.750
130.

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:58.870
If I can pick one that I could target with
a drug, do you really think it's going to

00:15:58.870 --> 00:16:00.570
make a major difference?

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:04.400
Remember, my field, cancer, we try to shrink
the disease by 50%.

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:06.990
That's called a win, and that's what we get
FDA approval on.

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:12.190
Well, 50% isn't even an order of magnitude
when you're talking hundreds of billions of

00:16:12.190 --> 00:16:13.190
cells.

00:16:13.190 --> 00:16:15.910
There's something missing here in what we're
doing.

00:16:15.910 --> 00:16:18.880
There's something missing in how we're approaching
these.

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:21.840
1997, I was a trainee at Sloan-Kettering.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:25.730
A kid, 25 year old kid, had germ cell tumor
of the brain, the lung, and the liver.

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:28.320
He went to the best hospitals in the country.

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:30.740
They told him, "Listen, chemotherapy is just
going to make you sick.

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:34.390
Why don't you go home to Texas and spend your
last couple months with your family?"

00:16:34.390 --> 00:16:37.140
Instead, this kid went to Indianapolis.

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:41.441
He went there because some goofball doc, and
I say the word goofball affectionately, he

00:16:41.441 --> 00:16:45.410
took two platinum electrodes and put it in
a gel and said, "Do cancerous cells like electricity

00:16:45.410 --> 00:16:46.410
or not?"

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:49.450
Well, it turns out, they didn't really care
about the electricity.

00:16:49.450 --> 00:16:52.780
But some of the platinum in those rods killed
some of the cells.

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:55.020
So they gave it-- This is the same thing in
my wedding band.

00:16:55.020 --> 00:16:57.490
They give it intravenously to this kid in
Indianapolis.

00:16:57.490 --> 00:17:02.570
A year and a half later, he won his first
of 7 Tours de France.

00:17:02.570 --> 00:17:06.720
Why did platinum cure Lance Armstrong?

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:08.860
I have no freaking idea.

00:17:08.860 --> 00:17:11.550
Yet you can find 50 explanations in the scientific
literature.

00:17:11.550 --> 00:17:14.540
"Well, it affects the DNA adducts and here
and here."

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:17.620
Again, we don't really know how these drugs
work.

00:17:17.620 --> 00:17:22.230
Most chemotherapy, I'll challenge you, I don't
think chemotherapy has any data that it actually

00:17:22.230 --> 00:17:23.720
touches the cancer cell.

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:28.360
It works, believe me, but it probably changes
your system so the cancer doesn't want to

00:17:28.360 --> 00:17:29.890
grow anymore.

00:17:29.890 --> 00:17:34.000
We don't have data that it actually targets
and hits the dividing cancer cells.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.750
Cancer cells are very similar to normal cells.

00:17:37.750 --> 00:17:42.100
So again, when you think of this complex emergent
system, we have to look at different ways

00:17:42.100 --> 00:17:46.910
of measuring the system, looking at perturbations,
when we look at disease.

00:17:46.910 --> 00:17:51.380
Remember, I'm the same field that put out
ads like this.

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:55.580
I'm the same field that put out ads like this.

00:17:55.580 --> 00:17:57.310
And this.

00:17:57.310 --> 00:17:58.580
And this.

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:02.330
You can't forget the dentists.

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:08.410
I'm the same field, that 25, 30 years ago
said, "Take margarine, not butter."

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:13.050
We killed millions of people by telling them
to do that.

00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:18.070
Over and over again, we make these declaratory
statements without any real data.

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:20.510
We make these observational findings.

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:26.470
There's an association of X with Y, and therefore,
we should avoid X.

00:18:26.470 --> 00:18:28.490
One of the things I'll talk to you about in
a minute is vitamins.

00:18:28.490 --> 00:18:32.930
Again, which gets people really upset, because
many people-- Vitamins have been a crutch

00:18:32.930 --> 00:18:35.100
which they're leaning on for the last several
decades.

00:18:35.100 --> 00:18:37.150
And I'm taking away that crutch.

00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:38.580
They get really upset.

00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:42.660
I spoke at the Commonwealth Club last night,
and I had protestors.

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:44.570
I've never had a protestor before.

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:48.900
It's true, I'm different than most people
in that the protestors were 85 years old.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:53.320
It's a very different kind of protestor who
protests with what I have to say.

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:56.980
But you'll look at things like vitamin D,
as we'll talk about.

00:18:56.980 --> 00:19:02.740
Right now, if you're over the age of 50, 60%
of people are taking vitamin D supplementation.

00:19:02.740 --> 00:19:07.300
The government in Canada had to outlaw vitamin
D testing because it was 11% of their healthcare

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:09.890
budget two years ago.

00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:11.670
Why are people testing for vitamin D?

00:19:11.670 --> 00:19:13.230
Because there are associations.

00:19:13.230 --> 00:19:16.950
People with lower vitamin D have a slightly
higher cancer rate and a slightly heart disease

00:19:16.950 --> 00:19:17.950
rate.

00:19:17.950 --> 00:19:21.280
Also, if you smoke, you have lower vitamin
D. If you're obese, you have lower vitamin

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:24.760
D. Nobody's saying if you give vitamin D,
you're going to stop smoking, but there's

00:19:24.760 --> 00:19:26.470
that association, too.

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:30.230
We'll talk about some of the data, because
it really has been leading us astray in many

00:19:30.230 --> 00:19:31.900
of the things we do.

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:35.400
One of the great examples is exercise.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:40.660
Our exercise notion in our country is: you
do an hour of exercise at the gym or the DVD

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:45.060
you put in your machine and watch and do some
yoga for an hour, and then you sit at your

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:46.340
desk the rest of the day.

00:19:46.340 --> 00:19:50.770
Well, if you start to look at the data, real
studies, and we'll talk about some of them,

00:19:50.770 --> 00:19:52.350
as old as 60 years old.

00:19:52.350 --> 00:19:55.670
The data shows that an hour of exercise a
day is awesome.

00:19:55.670 --> 00:19:59.490
You sit the rest of the day, you negate it
all, and it causes harm.

00:19:59.490 --> 00:20:03.870
In fact, that harm, if one does a quantitation
on incidence of heart disease, it's worse

00:20:03.870 --> 00:20:06.970
than smoking, if you look at it.

00:20:06.970 --> 00:20:09.100
So they key is moving.

00:20:09.100 --> 00:20:11.390
The original study done is the coolest study.

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:15.260
It was published in 1953 in the British medical
journal Lancet.

00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:16.260
Nobody paid attention to it.

00:20:16.260 --> 00:20:19.760
It wasn't referenced for literally 40 or 50
years.

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:23.250
They did something with privacy rules, now
nobody can do.

00:20:23.250 --> 00:20:27.650
This guy, Jeremiah Morris, went and looked
at the 26,000 workers in the British Transit

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:28.650
Authority.

00:20:28.650 --> 00:20:29.730
He just looked at all their data.

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:30.730
He didn't care who they were.

00:20:30.730 --> 00:20:32.230
He just looked at their data.

00:20:32.230 --> 00:20:35.160
What he said is that there were two classes
of employees.

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:38.500
There were the bus drivers that sat 90% of
the day and drove the buses.

00:20:38.500 --> 00:20:41.740
Then there were the ticket takers that walked
around and took the tickets on those double

00:20:41.740 --> 00:20:42.740
decker buses.

00:20:42.740 --> 00:20:47.770
Well, the heart disease deaths were 60% less
in the ticket takers compared to the bus drivers

00:20:47.770 --> 00:20:51.900
even though they weighed the same, they ate
the same, they lived in the same neighborhoods.

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:53.390
They had everything the same.

00:20:53.390 --> 00:20:56.700
The difference was one group sat and one group
walked.

00:20:56.700 --> 00:20:58.360
Powerful argument.

00:20:58.360 --> 00:21:00.150
He went further in that paper.

00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:02.610
This is one of the coolest graphs in science.

00:21:02.610 --> 00:21:06.160
It looks at death rate as associated with
profession.

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:10.850
What it showed is the worst professions were
hairdressers who stood in one place, or the

00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:12.300
typists who sat in one place.

00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:16.400
The best professions, believe it or not, were
the coal miners and the gardeners, because

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:18.350
they moved and they walked.

00:21:18.350 --> 00:21:25.020
Today, Nike is launching a product that's
called Fuel, which is a band which you wear.

00:21:25.020 --> 00:21:27.890
It looks at how much you move during the day.

00:21:27.890 --> 00:21:29.570
It communicates via Bluetooth.

00:21:29.570 --> 00:21:32.710
It creates these communities, because unfortunately
or fortunately, depending how you look at

00:21:32.710 --> 00:21:35.670
it, we all need competition to do the right
thing.

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:41.470
It's going to create competition among friends,
among corporations, employees, to start to

00:21:41.470 --> 00:21:44.460
move more during the day and quantitate it.

00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:46.790
Moving equates to better health.

00:21:46.790 --> 00:21:50.850
I wore one of those accelerometers and I realized
I was sitting most of the day.

00:21:50.850 --> 00:21:53.990
I got one of those phones that made me look
like an air traffic controller.

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:57.280
Now, when I'm in my office, I'm walking, talking
on the phone.

00:21:57.280 --> 00:22:00.450
I've reduced by half the amount of time I
sit.

00:22:00.450 --> 00:22:03.180
Someone comes to meet you during the day,
say, "Let's go for a walk."

00:22:03.180 --> 00:22:07.530
That's a sign of respect, rather than just
sitting in a conference room and talking.

00:22:07.530 --> 00:22:15.990
I know what a difference in corporate culture,
but over time, will make an enormous difference

00:22:15.990 --> 00:22:17.180
on health.

00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:20.900
Obviously, I talk a lot on negative stuff,
and what we're doing wrong.

00:22:20.900 --> 00:22:23.260
But obviously, we're doing things right.

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:27.860
If you look in the United States between 1900
and 2008, there's a dramatic increase in how

00:22:27.860 --> 00:22:29.210
long we live.

00:22:29.210 --> 00:22:34.720
True, much of that increase comes from reducing
infant mortality, because these data can be

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:36.200
somewhat misleading.

00:22:36.200 --> 00:22:42.640
If infants live past the age of 5, the chances
are they're going to live till they're 60.

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:44.950
That obviously skews the results to the right.

00:22:44.950 --> 00:22:48.850
Especially worldwide, now, we're starting
to eliminate much of infant mortality.

00:22:48.850 --> 00:22:51.190
But at the same time, we are living longer.

00:22:51.190 --> 00:22:53.610
So we are doing some things right.

00:22:53.610 --> 00:22:59.560
The problem, the fundamental problem, is that
evolution selects out for who has good kids.

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:02.210
It doesn't select out for who lives until
their 90s.

00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:03.700
We forget that sometimes.

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:08.480
In order to go to your 90s, you've got to
optimize a little, and tweak, because evolution

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:09.830
didn't take care of us.

00:23:09.830 --> 00:23:14.960
There are things that can help you during
childbearing years that may hurt you later

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:15.960
on.

00:23:15.960 --> 00:23:20.500
For example, if you skip your flu shot this
year, which I'm sure none of you did.

00:23:20.500 --> 00:23:23.880
If you skip your flu shot, and you got the
flu, you will all survive.

00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:24.890
I guarantee you.

00:23:24.890 --> 00:23:29.480
You'd have five, six, seven days of feeling
poor, etcetera, and then you'd go back to

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:31.370
work and you'd be fine.

00:23:31.370 --> 00:23:36.330
A decade from now, your risk of heart disease
and cancer are 10 and 12% elevated, because

00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:41.690
those five to seven days of marked inflammation
will have its manifestation a decade from

00:23:41.690 --> 00:23:42.690
now.

00:23:42.690 --> 00:23:47.110
Our culture is all about what will affect
us today, not tomorrow.

00:23:47.110 --> 00:23:50.160
We have to think more long term, as I'll show
you.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:53.280
US mortality, and this is--.

00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:57.780
Unfortunately the data is several years lagging,
always.

00:23:57.780 --> 00:24:01.920
If you look at it, a quarter of deaths are
heart disease.

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:07.350
Men higher than women, so 40% of us will die
of heart disease, about 20% of them women,

00:24:07.350 --> 00:24:09.010
will die of heart disease.

00:24:09.010 --> 00:24:12.750
Cancer, stroke, infections.

00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:16.320
Most of these things are delayable or preventable
by current technologies.

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:19.170
Yet most of the things we'll talk about we
ain't really doing.

00:24:19.170 --> 00:24:20.809
I'm not sure why.

00:24:20.809 --> 00:24:22.640
One of the technologies in full disclosure.

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:27.200
I'm a cofounder of Navigenics, one of the
DNA companies out there.

00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:28.780
You guys are an investor.

00:24:28.780 --> 00:24:31.440
Google was an original investor in Navigenics.

00:24:31.440 --> 00:24:36.650
I did it because the government had been spending
close to a billion dollars a year looking

00:24:36.650 --> 00:24:39.230
at gene associations with disease.

00:24:39.230 --> 00:24:42.580
And yet, nobody was using the data or benefiting
from it.

00:24:42.580 --> 00:24:49.730
So 1974, Monsanto's annual report, they set
150 million dollars to sequence one gene.

00:24:49.730 --> 00:24:52.650
Two weeks ago on Nightline, Bill Weir, the
