He wasn't eligible for screening."

00:25:37.380 --> 00:25:40.559
I'm like, "Are you guys serious?

00:25:40.559 --> 00:25:44.320
Either your criteria are wrong, because he
was positive.

00:25:44.320 --> 00:25:46.070
Something is missing in this picture here."

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:47.990
So then they said, "Well, you're right.

00:25:47.990 --> 00:25:50.090
Maybe the criteria can be changed a little.

00:25:50.090 --> 00:25:52.880
But technology's bad, and screening, and there
are problems with that."

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:56.810
I got, "Then you guys should be saying, 'Why
aren't we putting more research in technology

00:25:56.810 --> 00:25:58.540
to do better screening?'

00:25:58.540 --> 00:26:03.200
Just blanket saying, 'He shouldn't have been
screened because too many people will be screened',

00:26:03.200 --> 00:26:05.390
that's the wrong thing.

00:26:05.390 --> 00:26:08.220
So it really scares me in that regard.

00:26:08.220 --> 00:26:11.980
Many of you have already done this, but this
is me.

00:26:11.980 --> 00:26:14.500
These are my DNA results.

00:26:14.500 --> 00:26:16.990
Did it overnight tell me exactly what was
going on.

00:26:16.990 --> 00:26:17.990
No.

00:26:17.990 --> 00:26:22.010
But it was somewhat of a religious moment
for me, because all of a sudden, I looked

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:23.980
and I knew more about me.

00:26:23.980 --> 00:26:27.020
I realized I have a 42% chance of having a
heart attack.

00:26:27.020 --> 00:26:30.010
I had a normal cholesterol.

00:26:30.010 --> 00:26:31.470
Based on that, I went on a statin.

00:26:31.470 --> 00:26:32.740
We'll talk about that data in a minute.

00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:33.740
I'm on an aspirin.

00:26:33.740 --> 00:26:35.560
I'm lean body mass.

00:26:35.560 --> 00:26:36.560
I exercise.

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:37.560
I actually changed behaviors.

00:26:37.560 --> 00:26:38.560
I eat better.

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:40.380
When I saw myself on a piece of paper.

00:26:40.380 --> 00:26:44.410
We always view ourselves different than we
really are.

00:26:44.410 --> 00:26:47.330
It changed me.

00:26:47.330 --> 00:26:50.090
But it's not only your genes.

00:26:50.090 --> 00:26:53.530
This is a chart where the black is the genes,
the white is environment.

00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:57.511
Almost every disease, there's an environmental
part that we can control, and there's a genetic

00:26:57.511 --> 00:27:00.250
part that we can blame our parents for.

00:27:00.250 --> 00:27:04.400
Although we like to blame our parents for
everything, none of these diseases are deterministic.

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:06.780
They don't just happen.

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:08.280
We can prevent them.

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:14.020
Whether it be by behavior, changing environment,
or actually drugs, all of them can help.

00:27:14.020 --> 00:27:19.040
When we talk about drugs, and we'll talk more
about statins, but I get vilified saying I'm

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:20.930
a shill for the pharmaceutical company.

00:27:20.930 --> 00:27:22.200
"Agus is out there pushing drugs.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:24.110
He works for them.

00:27:24.110 --> 00:27:28.780
He doesn't want to push the natural things
because then he'll be out of business in treating

00:27:28.780 --> 00:27:29.780
disease."

00:27:29.780 --> 00:27:32.730
The drugs I push-- You know how much a statin
costs?

00:27:32.730 --> 00:27:38.190
Without health insurance, you can go to Wal-Mart
and get a 90 day supply for $9.

00:27:38.190 --> 00:27:39.350
These are generics.

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:40.610
These are available.

00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:46.370
These will radically change healthcare when
we start to look at the data.

00:27:46.370 --> 00:27:48.270
Aspirin.

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:53.520
An aspirin a day, $3 a year to take baby aspirin,
81 mg a year.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:58.170
If you start to look at the data, after five
years of aspirin, death due to GI cancer down

00:27:58.170 --> 00:28:00.490
54%.

00:28:00.490 --> 00:28:04.970
One case of colon cancer to a company like
Google costs $247,000.

00:28:04.970 --> 00:28:12.390
Again, if you can reduce that by half by saying,
"Take an aspirin", I don't get why people

00:28:12.390 --> 00:28:14.450
aren't doing it more.

00:28:14.450 --> 00:28:15.670
After 20 years, death.

00:28:15.670 --> 00:28:17.690
Death is a bad side effect.

00:28:17.690 --> 00:28:19.850
Death due to prostate cancer down 10%.

00:28:19.850 --> 00:28:21.870
Lung cancer, 30%.

00:28:21.870 --> 00:28:25.610
Colo-rectal cancer, 40, esophageal cancer,
60%.

00:28:25.610 --> 00:28:28.390
You start to look at this data.

00:28:28.390 --> 00:28:31.930
You start to say-- Listen, I'm not saying
anybody should take a pill.

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:35.820
But I'm saying that conversation with a physician
needs to happen.

00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:39.290
You need to say, because there are reasons
why you shouldn't be on it.

00:28:39.290 --> 00:28:43.420
But you need to have to conversation and say,
"Listen, I understand there's data.

00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:44.420
This may benefit me.

00:28:44.420 --> 00:28:45.860
What are the downsides?

00:28:45.860 --> 00:28:50.980
Talk about me as an individual, given my family
history, given my genetics, given my risk

00:28:50.980 --> 00:28:52.059
factors.

00:28:52.059 --> 00:28:54.840
I want to know why I'm not on something like
this."

00:28:54.840 --> 00:29:00.360
If you're a company and you say to your employees,
"Listen, you can do whatever you want.

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:02.850
But if you have that discussion with your
doctor, I'm going to give you a discount on

00:29:02.850 --> 00:29:06.340
your health insurance, because it's going
to benefit us."

00:29:06.340 --> 00:29:12.470
Michael Dell was a hero to me in that he said,
"Listen, I have 105,000 employees at Dell.

00:29:12.470 --> 00:29:14.000
They're welcome to smoke.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:18.450
But if they smoke, they're going to have a
different health insurance cost than the non-smokers.

00:29:18.450 --> 00:29:23.570
Because why should smokers be subsidized by
the non-smokers?"

00:29:23.570 --> 00:29:25.800
That data are profound.

00:29:25.800 --> 00:29:27.920
We need to push and change.

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:29.270
Obviously, it's aggressive.

00:29:29.270 --> 00:29:30.520
People would get upset.

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:34.660
But we're the number one spender in healthcare
in the world, and our results are dismal.

00:29:34.660 --> 00:29:38.380
16 1/2% of GDP and growing every year.

00:29:38.380 --> 00:29:44.350
Unless we start to enact things and change
and prevent, it ain't going to get smaller.

00:29:44.350 --> 00:29:46.220
You start to look at drugs like statins.

00:29:46.220 --> 00:29:50.580
Again, these are prescription drugs now, although
about 6 months ago, they were filed to go

00:29:50.580 --> 00:29:51.580
over-the-counter.

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:52.580
They're generic.

00:29:52.580 --> 00:30:00.200
Again, they are inexpensive, costing about
$36 for an entire year of treatment.

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:02.020
You start to look at the data.

00:30:02.020 --> 00:30:05.230
The Jupiter study, which was really a pivotal
study because it took people who had normal

00:30:05.230 --> 00:30:06.230
cholesterol.

00:30:06.230 --> 00:30:07.850
A normal cholesterol.

00:30:07.850 --> 00:30:10.309
Not a high cholesterol, a normal cholesterol.

00:30:10.309 --> 00:30:12.180
They put them on a pill a day.

00:30:12.180 --> 00:30:16.770
What it did was it delayed heart attack and
stroke by over a decade.

00:30:16.770 --> 00:30:20.750
Many cancers reduced their incidence by double
digit percentages.

00:30:20.750 --> 00:30:24.270
Yes, a percent of people or less will have
some side effects.

00:30:24.270 --> 00:30:25.270
It's 100% reversible.

00:30:25.270 --> 00:30:26.809
If you have it, you stop.

00:30:26.809 --> 00:30:32.350
But again, if we can have this dramatic effect
on disease, why aren't we using it more?

00:30:32.350 --> 00:30:34.060
The cost is so low.

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:37.070
Again, I'm not getting why we're not doing
it.

00:30:37.070 --> 00:30:40.440
And yet, we do the other side, which is we
take pills.

00:30:40.440 --> 00:30:44.250
Ends up costing more than these pills I just
talked about.

00:30:44.250 --> 00:30:47.400
39,000 women tracked over 19 years.

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:52.270
You can criticize all the study all you want,
but they looked at women who took vitamins.

00:30:52.270 --> 00:30:57.910
Vitamin B6, folic acid, and copper, and iron
versus women who didn't.

00:30:57.910 --> 00:31:00.630
Actually, the women who took the vitamins
were healthier baseline.

00:31:00.630 --> 00:31:01.970
They were skinnier.

00:31:01.970 --> 00:31:04.390
They had less diabetes.

00:31:04.390 --> 00:31:07.030
They looked at them and said, "What's the
difference in the outcome?

00:31:07.030 --> 00:31:11.290
Well, a 15% higher death rate in the women
who took the supplements."

00:31:11.290 --> 00:31:16.110
15% higher death rate in the women who took
the supplements.

00:31:16.110 --> 00:31:19.160
I look at that and I say, "Whew.

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:22.740
By the year 2004, 65% of women in this country
were taking supplements."

00:31:22.740 --> 00:31:26.910
I said, "There's got to be some data behind
it, or why would all these women be doing

00:31:26.910 --> 00:31:27.910
it?

00:31:27.910 --> 00:31:33.340
Why would it be a multi, multibillion dollar
industry if there weren't some benefit there

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:34.340
to it?"

00:31:34.340 --> 00:31:36.710
Then I look on the internet, and this is just
in the last couple months.

00:31:36.710 --> 00:31:40.800
These are all the headlines about vitamin
D. According to this, it can cure every disease

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:42.320
known to mankind.

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:44.080
I mean, that's great.

00:31:44.080 --> 00:31:46.850
Then I look and said, "There's got to be data
here.

00:31:46.850 --> 00:31:49.420
There's got to be data why this happens."

00:31:49.420 --> 00:31:54.870
In the United States, now, over 75% of us
are quote low in vitamin D. There's data that

00:31:54.870 --> 00:31:59.080
there's an epidemic of low vitamin D over
the last decade.

00:31:59.080 --> 00:32:03.230
As we spend more time indoors, wear sunscreen,
vitamin D levels are coming down.

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:06.179
Yet, hip fracture rates are also down over
that same period.

00:32:06.179 --> 00:32:10.630
So it starts to make you wonder why is that
really the case?

00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:11.630
What is normal?

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:13.160
Who defines what a normal value is?

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:17.450
When I was born, I didn't come with an ingredient
manual that says, "Your normal value of vitamin

00:32:17.450 --> 00:32:18.490
D should be X."

00:32:18.490 --> 00:32:22.559
Because remember, vitamin D is a network,
not an individual node.

00:32:22.559 --> 00:32:27.170
There's vitamin D, there's the receptor, and
then there are six signaling molecules.

00:32:27.170 --> 00:32:30.100
All we're measuring is one part of a network.

00:32:30.100 --> 00:32:34.070
So if you've low vitamin D, it probably means
you've got a high binding receptor.

00:32:34.070 --> 00:32:35.929
Or you've got an elevated number of receptors.

00:32:35.929 --> 00:32:39.820
Or one of the signaling molecules is a little
bit higher than somebody else.

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:43.490
Yet, we look at this and we all start saying,
"Hey, we're low in vitamin D.

00:32:43.490 --> 00:32:45.200
We've got to correct that."

00:32:45.200 --> 00:32:49.470
But part of it comes from the notion that
if you go to your doctor and he or she draws

00:32:49.470 --> 00:32:52.830
arbitrary lab values, because unfortunately
most of them are somewhat arbitrary, and they

00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:55.030
say, "Come back in a year", you say, "Listen.

00:32:55.030 --> 00:32:56.030
I shouldn't have gone.

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:58.010
There was no value from going to my doctor.

00:32:58.010 --> 00:32:59.090
That wellness visit.

00:32:59.090 --> 00:33:00.090
He didn't tell me to do anything.

00:33:00.090 --> 00:33:01.510
Or she didn't say anything different."

00:33:01.510 --> 00:33:03.060
They say, "Vitamin D's low.

00:33:03.060 --> 00:33:05.490
Take vitamin D." You perceive value.

00:33:05.490 --> 00:33:08.660
That physician perceives they gave you value.

00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:11.230
That perception is key.

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:14.950
About 2 and 1/2 years ago, the World Health
Organization came out with a blanket statement

00:33:14.950 --> 00:33:17.450
saying, "Cell phones may cause brain cancer."

00:33:17.450 --> 00:33:20.630
There was a panic around the world.

00:33:20.630 --> 00:33:24.330
If you start to look at what is the root data
they went on, what they did was they looked

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:26.590
at 26,000 people with brain cancers.

00:33:26.590 --> 00:33:32.420
They asked the brain cancer patient and the
spouse, "How much did you use the cell phone?"

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:36.210
When they answered, it was almost 2 and 1/2
times more in the brain cancer patient than

00:33:36.210 --> 00:33:37.210
the spouse.

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:38.470
So spouses are a good control.

00:33:38.470 --> 00:33:42.410
Pretty similar genetics, same environment,
eat the same, live the same.

00:33:42.410 --> 00:33:44.170
And 2 and 1/2 [inaudible] more cell phone
usage.

00:33:44.170 --> 00:33:46.410
Well, clearly, there may be an association.

00:33:46.410 --> 00:33:50.120
A clever group went and said, "Let's audit
the cell phone records, because we can do

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:51.120
that."

00:33:51.120 --> 00:33:56.430
They went back and they were exactly the same,
because human perception is we blame something.

00:33:56.430 --> 00:33:59.320
"I have brain cancer, I must have done something
wrong.

00:33:59.320 --> 00:34:00.640
Well, the cell phone, that's why.

00:34:00.640 --> 00:34:01.940
I talk on the cell phone."

00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:04.600
So they perceive they did it differently.

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:08.349
You went to breast cancer patients, 2000 breast
cancer patients, and you say, "What was your

00:34:08.349 --> 00:34:10.889
diet before and after you were diagnosed with
breast cancer?"

00:34:10.889 --> 00:34:13.440
Uniformly, the women said, "My diet was horrible.

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:14.440
I have breast cancer.

00:34:14.440 --> 00:34:15.440
I saw the light.

00:34:15.440 --> 00:34:16.440
Now I'm healthy."

00:34:16.440 --> 00:34:20.340
When they went back and audited what they
ate, it was exactly the same.

00:34:20.340 --> 00:34:23.090
So again, human nature is we've got to blame
something.

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:25.770
There's something-- When something bad happens,
something's wrong.

00:34:25.770 --> 00:34:30.260
"Something happens to my child, it must be
that vaccine they got, because there's got

00:34:30.260 --> 00:34:31.780
to be a reason for it."

00:34:31.780 --> 00:34:34.730
Or "If I have this problem, it's got to be
because of something I did or something in

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:36.179
the environment", etcetera.

00:34:36.179 --> 00:34:37.619
We all want to blame something.

00:34:37.619 --> 00:34:41.840
But let's go back and look at the data of
vitamin D. They took women 70 years and older,

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:45.660
over 2000 of them, and they gave them a very
high dose of vitamin D. That raised their

00:34:45.660 --> 00:34:49.470
serum vitamin D level for a year.

00:34:49.470 --> 00:34:51.730
26% higher fracture rate.

00:34:51.730 --> 00:34:53.090
Not lower.

00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:55.380
Higher fracture rate.

00:34:55.380 --> 00:35:01.930
So all of a sudden, women are taking vitamin
D to increase their bone density and prevent

00:35:01.930 --> 00:35:02.930
fractures.

00:35:02.930 --> 00:35:07.750
And yet, this is a very well respected journal
with a couple thousand patients.

00:35:07.750 --> 00:35:09.950
So an increase in bone fracture rate.

00:35:09.950 --> 00:35:10.950
Hmm.

00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:12.640
Remember, the body's homeostatic.

00:35:12.640 --> 00:35:17.250
You take a bolus of something, you down-regulate
receptors and you screw up the signaling.

00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:19.350
What's the only reason we tan?

00:35:19.350 --> 00:35:21.850
To block vitamin D absorption.

00:35:21.850 --> 00:35:27.109
Right there, evolution has a very difficult
way, it requires a lot of energy, that we've

00:35:27.109 --> 00:35:32.080
evolved so we don't have too much vitamin
D. Yet we take these big boluses of pills

00:35:32.080 --> 00:35:33.080
all the time.

00:35:33.080 --> 00:35:35.690
Then, well, "maybe the dose was too high."

00:35:35.690 --> 00:35:44.480
So they did a study in women where they took
women-- oh!-- who, in the nurses' health studies.

00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:47.080
Again, over 20,000 women were looked at.

00:35:47.080 --> 00:35:50.510
They gave them vitamin D and calcium.

00:35:50.510 --> 00:35:53.220
The regular vitamin D and calcium that most
people take.

00:35:53.220 --> 00:35:55.710
The Os-Cal D or whatever brand it is.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:36:00.170
In that study, there was no effect on bone
fracture by taking calcium and vitamin D.

00:36:00.170 --> 00:36:04.251
There were side effects that caused kidney
stones, it affected gastric upset, all of

00:36:04.251 --> 00:36:05.430
those things.

00:36:05.430 --> 00:36:06.930
Yet no benefit.

00:36:06.930 --> 00:36:12.580
Most women, most women over the age of 60,
take calcium and vitamin D.

00:36:12.580 --> 00:36:15.490
The first question to ask your doctor if they
say, "You should be on calcium and vitamin

00:36:15.490 --> 00:36:16.990
D" is "Why?"

00:36:16.990 --> 00:36:20.460
Osteoporosis, we know, is a genetic disorder.

00:36:20.460 --> 00:36:23.560
Taking calcium and vitamin D doesn't make
it better.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:24.670
Yet we do it.

00:36:24.670 --> 00:36:27.830
Again, something a little screwy there, in
my mind.

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:28.830
And then this study.

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:34.200
This was a $240 million study, almost a quarter
billion dollars stamped by the US government.

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:35.200
Vitamin E.

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:37.210
We know vitamin E's a great antioxidant.

00:36:37.210 --> 00:36:39.440
Everybody's taking it to prevent prostate
cancer.

00:36:39.440 --> 00:36:42.010
Let's see how much it prevents prostate cancer.

00:36:42.010 --> 00:36:43.770
So they gave men 400 units.

00:36:43.770 --> 00:36:46.210
This is the same amount in a multivitamin.

00:36:46.210 --> 00:36:47.210
They gave them that.

00:36:47.210 --> 00:36:48.670
After three years, they halted the study.

00:36:48.670 --> 00:36:50.530
A quarter billion dollar study.

00:36:50.530 --> 00:36:51.530
Why?

00:36:51.530 --> 00:36:55.230
Because there was a 17% higher incidence of
prostate cancer in the men who took vitamin

00:36:55.230 --> 00:36:59.580
E. That lasted for three, four years after
stopping the vitamin.

00:36:59.580 --> 00:37:04.000
A 17% increase in the most common non skin
cancer in men.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:05.869
First of all, the impact on the individual
is staggering.

00:37:05.869 --> 00:37:11.570
The impact on society, on companies, on our
health insurance, is staggering because we're

00:37:11.570 --> 00:37:13.050
taking this.

00:37:13.050 --> 00:37:15.970
Again, what am I missing here?

00:37:15.970 --> 00:37:23.130
We're talking a $20 to 30 billion impact on
healthcare by this excess in men diagnosed

00:37:23.130 --> 00:37:24.720
with prostate cancer.

00:37:24.720 --> 00:37:25.720
Then you look.

00:37:25.720 --> 00:37:27.150
The government said, "Listen.

00:37:27.150 --> 00:37:28.910
Maybe there are some studies that we're missing
here."

00:37:28.910 --> 00:37:35.000
So they looked at 63 studies with more than
500 people in a randomized fashion with multivitamins

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:36.740
and heart disease and cancer.

00:37:36.740 --> 00:37:38.420
None of them showed a benefit.

00:37:38.420 --> 00:37:40.530
Zero showed a benefit.

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:43.170
I've just showed you a number of studies with
clear negatives.

00:37:43.170 --> 00:37:46.640
And yet, none has yet shown a benefit.

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:51.460
In 2004, they looked and they said, "People
who smoked, or former smokers, we've got to

00:37:51.460 --> 00:37:55.460
give them high dose antioxidants to prevent
lung cancer, because they're dying like in

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:57.730
droves of lung cancer."

00:37:57.730 --> 00:38:02.359
28% higher lung cancer when they took these
supplements.

00:38:02.359 --> 00:38:06.380
17% higher death rate when they took these
supplements.

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:10.870
Again, pills, I'm not sure they actually have
benefits.

00:38:10.870 --> 00:38:13.390
Clearly, they're causing harm.

00:38:13.390 --> 00:38:17.700
The other side of the equation is looking
at how technology's going to fit in.

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:21.630
Because clearly, there probably are some people
that benefit from taking pills.

00:38:21.630 --> 00:38:24.240
If you're pregnant, you need to take prenatal
vitamins.

00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:28.170
There's certain eye conditions were vitamins
have been shown to help.

00:38:28.170 --> 00:38:29.760
Maybe some people with their diet need it.

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:34.109
But we need technology to start to say who
needs what, because blanket statements like

00:38:34.109 --> 00:38:37.640
I'm making probably aren't the best thing
going forward.

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:42.940
In 1976, if you thought you were pregnant,
or your spouse thought she was pregnant, you

00:38:42.940 --> 00:38:46.300
took a tube of blood, you went to a hospital
because it couldn't be done anywhere but a

00:38:46.300 --> 00:38:47.300
hospital.

00:38:47.300 --> 00:38:49.420
Every hospital in the country had a rabbit
floor.

00:38:49.420 --> 00:38:52.680
We took that blood, and we injected it into
a poor rabbit.

00:38:52.680 --> 00:38:56.870
Five days later, we sacrificed the rabbit
and we looked at the rabbits ovaries.

00:38:56.870 --> 00:38:59.910
If they were enlarged, you were pregnant.

00:38:59.910 --> 00:39:02.580
That was the state of the art in 1976.

00:39:02.580 --> 00:39:06.500
Well, 1977, the first proteomic test was approved
by the FDA.

00:39:06.500 --> 00:39:11.360
It was a $10 urine-based test for pregnancy.

00:39:11.360 --> 00:39:13.370
Rabbits over the world rejoiced.

00:39:13.370 --> 00:39:16.730
[laughter] All of a sudden, we had a binary
outcome.

00:39:16.730 --> 00:39:18.270
Yes/no whether you're pregnant or not.

00:39:18.270 --> 00:39:23.671
It radically changed reproductive health,
women's health, child mortality because we

00:39:23.671 --> 00:39:26.470
can actually give prenatal vitamins, we can
take care of women because we knew they were

00:39:26.470 --> 00:39:28.000
pregnant.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:29.410
Changed everything.

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:31.840
We need more technologies like this.

00:39:31.840 --> 00:39:36.359
We now have the capacity with newer technology,
to actually bring them in.

00:39:36.359 --> 00:39:37.359
This is the proteomics.

00:39:37.359 --> 00:39:38.359
This is the cover on the book.

00:39:38.359 --> 00:39:42.820
This is that 20,000 foot view of the state
of the system, where, instead of--.

00:39:42.820 --> 00:39:46.869
In our country, we do a colonoscopy at age
50, because that's where the risk rewards

00:39:46.869 --> 00:39:49.240
come together, and that's what's cost effective.

00:39:49.240 --> 00:39:50.240
I love that word.

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:51.520
It's cost effective to do.

00:39:51.520 --> 00:39:55.590
Well, what do you say to the 4000 people in
the United States last year who died of colon

00:39:55.590 --> 00:39:57.320
cancer under the age of 40?

00:39:57.320 --> 00:40:00.040
"You weren't cost effective?"

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:04.610
What do you say to the fact that only 17%
of people who should have colonoscopies do,

00:40:04.610 --> 00:40:06.980
at age 50?

00:40:06.980 --> 00:40:10.300
What if we had a blood test to say who had
a colonic polyp?

00:40:10.300 --> 00:40:11.980
First of all, we would do it in the right
people.

00:40:11.980 --> 00:40:13.440
We'd have almost 100% compliance.

00:40:13.440 --> 00:40:15.810
And the other is, we have a quality metric.

00:40:15.810 --> 00:40:18.100
Did that doc get the polyp our or not?

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:20.430
Because right now, there is no quality metric.

00:40:20.430 --> 00:40:23.650
That's what technology can do, is start to
personalize things.

00:40:23.650 --> 00:40:26.060
We're not far away from that.

00:40:26.060 --> 00:40:28.530
There's a newer technology coming out that's
pretty wild.

00:40:28.530 --> 00:40:34.320
Turns out, you and I have 10 fold more bacteria
in us than we do cells in our body.

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:38.220
If someone is in China, you look at the incidence
of prostate cancer and breast cancer, it's

00:40:38.220 --> 00:40:40.030
1/10 what ours is.

00:40:40.030 --> 00:40:43.190
After they move to the United States, after
a decade, it starts to approach ours.

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:45.340
"Well, then it's the Burger King and the McDonald's."

00:40:45.340 --> 00:40:47.470
Turns out, that's not the case.

00:40:47.470 --> 00:40:49.500
It's the bacteria in the water.

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:51.110
It's our microbiome.

00:40:51.110 --> 00:40:52.710
They get populated with our bacteria.

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:55.540
Well, those bacteria, they control how you
metabolize your food.

00:40:55.540 --> 00:40:56.970
They control your hormone levels.

00:40:56.970 --> 00:41:01.280
For the first time ever this year, we've learned
to quantitate them and actually look at what

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:03.430
type are populating what individual.

00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:07.040
I guarantee you, over the next several years,
we're going to start to modulate them to reduce

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:10.470
risk for disease, which will be powerful.

00:41:10.470 --> 00:41:12.410
I'm a believer in prevention.

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:13.540
I look at the data.

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:16.780
There are little things one can do that can
radically affect health.

00:41:16.780 --> 00:41:22.230
In the Framingham heart study, one of the
most protective effects wasn't what you ate,

00:41:22.230 --> 00:41:23.680
it wasn't your weight.

00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:26.109
It was actually owning a dog.

00:41:26.109 --> 00:41:27.109
We look at the data.

00:41:27.109 --> 00:41:28.109
"A dog?

00:41:28.109 --> 00:41:29.109
Well, it relaxes you."

00:41:29.109 --> 00:41:30.170
Well, it's not that it relaxes you.

00:41:30.170 --> 00:41:31.890
It puts you on a regular schedule.

00:41:31.890 --> 00:41:37.070
If you start to look at the data on regularity,
it is profound for health.

00:41:37.070 --> 00:41:41.450
If you have your lunch today at noon, and
then tomorrow at 2:00, for two hours, stress

00:41:41.450 --> 00:41:42.869
hormones go up.

00:41:42.869 --> 00:41:45.310
When stress hormones go up, the body goes
in a protective mode.

00:41:45.310 --> 00:41:46.310
It says, "Hey, listen.

00:41:46.310 --> 00:41:47.310
There might be a lion coming.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:48.820
I've got to really save energy.

00:41:48.820 --> 00:41:50.109
I've got to shut down."

00:41:50.109 --> 00:41:53.790
So you get about a 25-30% decrease in cognition.

00:41:53.790 --> 00:41:57.410
You get about a 36% decrease in exercise performance.

00:41:57.410 --> 00:42:02.140
You actually gain weight because you lower
metabolism dramatically to try to save energy.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:07.570
So if you eat on a regular schedule, sleep
on a regular schedule, dramatic effect on

00:42:07.570 --> 00:42:08.570
health.

00:42:08.570 --> 00:42:12.720
It's the person who randomly goes by places
like this and grabs and apple that hurt themselves.

00:42:12.720 --> 00:42:17.050
If you have an apple every day at 3:00, greatest
thing in the world.

00:42:17.050 --> 00:42:20.109
Regularity is key.

00:42:20.109 --> 00:42:22.550
Almost as important as what you eat.

00:42:22.550 --> 00:42:27.800
Very powerful, costs nothing, and can have
a dramatic effect on health.

