00:47:52.210 --> 00:47:54.710
It's public that I was one of Steve Jobs'
doctors.

00:47:54.710 --> 00:47:57.390
He puts in his book how we sequenced his genome.

00:47:57.390 --> 00:47:58.390
We didn't sequenced his genome.

00:47:58.390 --> 00:47:59.839
We sequenced a couple of genes.

00:47:59.839 --> 00:48:02.770
We looked at it, and everything we did was
part of clinical trials.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:04.690
He went on drugs, and so did everybody else
there.

00:48:04.690 --> 00:48:06.500
I'm a believer in trials.

00:48:06.500 --> 00:48:10.250
I'm a believer in doing randomized clinical
trials, or clinical trials that are single

00:48:10.250 --> 00:48:12.730
armed to see if these drugs work.

00:48:12.730 --> 00:48:14.280
And many of them do.

00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:16.670
I chair one of the brain cancer foundations.

00:48:16.670 --> 00:48:20.210
About seven or eight years ago, I got a call
from a doctor in Galveston, Texas, who said,

00:48:20.210 --> 00:48:24.119
"I give this drug called Avastin, a Genentech
drug, to a patient with glioblastoma, and

00:48:24.119 --> 00:48:25.119
it worked."

00:48:25.119 --> 00:48:26.119
I go, "There's no way.

00:48:26.119 --> 00:48:27.630
It's too big to even get across the blood-brain
barrier."

00:48:27.630 --> 00:48:29.700
This story's in the book.

00:48:29.700 --> 00:48:30.770
She said, "Well, here are the scans.

00:48:30.770 --> 00:48:31.780
They look real."

00:48:31.780 --> 00:48:33.410
So we did a trial on people who failed chemo.

00:48:33.410 --> 00:48:35.400
They have weeks to live.

00:48:35.400 --> 00:48:38.500
And at six months, nobody progressed.

00:48:38.500 --> 00:48:42.000
This drug that didn't even cross the blood-brain
barrier worked because it bound a protein

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:44.240
and lowered the pressure of the cancer.

00:48:44.240 --> 00:48:46.460
When you lower the pressure, the cancer stops
growing.

00:48:46.460 --> 00:48:50.349
A year later, it's FDA approved and standard
treatment for brain cancer.

00:48:50.349 --> 00:48:53.510
So we need to keep our eyes open and learn
from every experience.

00:48:53.510 --> 00:48:55.850
Be they with somebody who's a little questionable
or not.

00:48:55.850 --> 00:49:01.050
But right now, all we do is we have to report
the negatives to the FDA, the side effects

00:49:01.050 --> 00:49:02.050
to the FDA.

00:49:02.050 --> 00:49:04.560
I have a good response, a cure, I never have
to report it.

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:05.760
Nobody knows about it.

00:49:05.760 --> 00:49:06.760
It's hidden.

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:08.119
We need to change that.

00:49:08.119 --> 00:49:09.450
We need to get data out there.

00:49:09.450 --> 00:49:14.560
We need to talk about our experiences and
learn from them, because we're not now.

